text: Okay, I was made aware of the changes long before the release of the trailer, so I went in with an open mind. Though I don't prefer the movies over the books, I love the casting and who doesn't like seeing one of their favorite book series brought to life? I trust Dashner's judgment, so I'll accept the changes that have been made. When I first watched it, I had no idea what to make of it. But I read an interesting comment down below saying that they think instead of forcing them into the Scorch for a "cure", they decided to trick them instead, making it seem as if their ventures are their escape. Regardless, I'm super excited to see it!

text: Well, it looks ok, I guess. But it certainly looks like a pretty big departure from the book. I was fine with most of the changes in the first movie, because that book had a lot of elements that just wouldn't work in a film. Scorch, however, is a very simple, straight-up survival thriller that would *not* be very hard to translate to the screen. Maybe I'm being picky, (after all, it's just one trailer) but I really loved this book, and I don't want to see it ruined. All that said, I'm still  #ReadyForScorch !

text: Looks to me as they combined book two and three. Wich I think is okay. The story as it's told in the books is very difficult to convey to screen. There was a lot of mystery and confusion. Wih is fine if you know there is a third book that explains everything, but not if you're watching a movie. In a movie, a little mystery is captivating and keeps you watching, too much and it gets too confusing to follow.  The book heavily depended on Thomas's thoughts and interpretations of things, flashbacks and telekenisis. It is very hard, if not impossible, to convey that to a movie without being clich√©.  I think they have made some difficult choices regarding the book plot, but I think it was neccesary to do the story justice.

text: I'm very happy that they made enormous amendments to the original book. Where the original Maze Runner book was somewhat interesting and compelling, every book after were lacking in originality and conceptuality ( Not detracting that the original premise and the whole idea has very little appeal by the time you figure out the whole story in the 3rd book).  The Scorch Trial book when it came down to it was a glorified zombie thriller that did little to advance the plot and largely had very few interesting parts. text: This looks like a solid movie. The first one had some weak moments, but was a surprisingly good movie. This one looks like it has an even stronger storyline, and this trailer has set my expectations pretty high.¬† And to everyone saying "The book is wayyyy better," let me ask you. Have you EVER said "the movie is wayyyy better than the book"? Probably not. Because you can't really compare them. A book and a movie are two very, VERY different things. They are completely different forms of entertainment. You simply cannot include every single detail of a book in a movie. That's why it's called an adaptation, it's clearly the same story but with some changes. What works on a page does not always work well on the screen. The author has said over and over again that he is perfectly fine with the changes, and he's even said that they make more sense.¬† So please, understand that basically all book-to-movie adaptations have changes made to them. You should expect that by now, seriously. Stop expecting them to be the same, and then you won't be disappointed.¬† I have understood for a long time that books and movies simply can't really be compared, you have to go into them realizing that they are two different things. I've read this entire series, and I'm fine with the changes to the movies. They work on the big screen. This movie looks really, really good and I can't wait to see it, no matter how many changes they made.

text: I remember having my doubts on reading the books because of all the bad reviews it got. But once I started, I couldn't stop. And then I heard they were going to adapt it into a movie, and I just had to see it. I had doubts then too, because before anything else, I'm an avid reader. But they did an amazing job with the first movie, and it looks like they did an amazing job for this one, and I can't wait to see it. My point?  As¬†an avid reader, I understand why people want the movies to be at least 95% like the books. But also speaking as a film fanatic, I also know movie adaptations are never going to be exactly like the books. But as long as they've kept the general storyline/setting/characters the same, I'm not too fussed (unless they majorly change something). What I'm trying to say is, book readers, don't judge a movie until you've actually seen it (open mind and all that), and film fanatics, know that you may not understand something unless you've read the books, so either do that or research on the stuff you don't understand.

text: Ehh... I didn't like the first movie, but at least that one got the tone right. The second book is way more gritty compared to this trailer. By gritty I mean not looking like a stroll along a beach w/o water. Remember the scenes in the book where the rescuers were all hung and mutilated, or when if they would've posed for the trailer shot in the desert all their skin would've peeled off, or the cranks in the sewers that looked like rotting crack addicts from the Bronx. The book managed to have all that and not seem like exploitation. Luckily, you can still kind of read the second book right after watching the first movie, and even from just this trailer I can tell you it would be a much better experience than watching it.

text: The director did such a formulaic job of timing and foreshadowing what was going to happen that my kid and I were predicting and quoting lines of dialog before they were spoken by the characters.  The predictability and formulas were not too detracting, as usual, you just waited for the kicker line, and then the  action sequence, and go "yeah called it!"   Like any good rollercoaster, you see the hill coming before you plummet, and that makes it fun.    Story-wise, yeah, totally different from the novel, but improved, in my opinion.  Certain things like character allegiances and motivations that Dashner left frustatingly hazy were made pointedly clear in the screenplay, the effect for me being one of relief rather than ire.   Cool movie.  Though I don't for the life of me know why they released it a day ahead of schedule.  Every website, trailer, online and, poster and playbill says Sep 18, and the theaters around here all released it this evening at 8pm.
